---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Mosskeep Frog" description="A small moss-backed frog of Vaelinya.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <p class="eyebrow">World · Animals</p>
    <h1>Mosskeep Frog</h1>
    <p class="lede">A small green frog with moss growing on its back. It carries moisture, moss spores, and tiny seed-life between wet stones and shaded paths.</p>

    <figure class="panel animal-portrait">
      <picture>
        <source
          media="(max-width: 560px)"
          srcset="/assets/images/vaelinya/animals/mosskeep-frog-v01-512-q.png"
        />
        <source
          media="(max-width: 900px)"
          srcset="/assets/images/vaelinya/animals/mosskeep-frog-v01-768-q.png"
        />
        <img
          src="/assets/images/vaelinya/animals/mosskeep-frog-v01-1024-q.png"
          alt="Mosskeep Frog, a colourful blue-green-gold frog with golden eyes and a living moss garden of tiny flowers, seed pods, and dew-orbs growing across its back."
          loading="eager"
          decoding="async"
          width="1024"
          height="1024"
        />
      </picture>
      <figcaption>Mosskeep Frog, shown as a transparent cutout so it can sit gently inside different Vaelinya pages.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <article class="visual-callout visual-callout-world">
      <div class="visual-callout-mark" aria-hidden="true"><span>☘</span></div>
      <div class="visual-callout-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Small wonder</p>
        <h2>A moving patch of moss</h2>
        <p>Mosskeep Frogs are small wetland creatures of moss, shade, stone, and quiet water. They are easy to miss until they move.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Where it lives</h2>
      <p>Mosskeep Frogs are usually seen near wet bridge stones, shaded pools, old walls, moss beds, tree roots, cave mouths, and damp path edges.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>How to recognise it</h2>
      <p>A Mosskeep Frog has a deep green body, soft moss across the back, tiny fern-specks or seed-specks in the moss, golden-brown eyes, and damp stone-coloured feet.</p>
      <p>It looks partly like a frog and partly like a small moving patch of moss.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Sound and movement</h2>
      <p>Its call is a low wet chirrup, almost like one drop of water landing in moss. The sound is quiet. A child might hear it before seeing the frog.</p>
      <p>Mosskeep Frogs move in short careful hops. They cross from stone to stone, root to root, and moss patch to moss patch.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>What it does in the world</h2>
      <p>Mosskeep Frogs carry moss spores, dew, tiny fern-specks, wetland seed-life, and small insects in their moss. They help damp places stay connected.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Related animals</h2>
      <div class="link-list">
        <a href="/world/animals/amethyst-orblight/">Amethyst Orblight</a>
        <a href="/world/animals/hearthcrest-caller/">Hearthcrest Caller</a>
        <a href="/world/animals/">Animals of Vaelinya</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Accessibility note</p>
      <p>Mosskeep Frogs are small green frogs with moss growing on their backs. They carry moisture and moss spores between wet stones, roots, and shaded paths.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
